        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "## Standard Electrode Potential of Cu²⁺/Cu⁰\n\nThe standard reduction potential for the half-reaction:\n\n> **Cu²⁺(aq) + 2e⁻ → Cu(s)**\n\nis:\n\n| Half-Reaction | E° (V vs. SHE) | Conditions |\n|---|---|---|\n| Cu²⁺ + 2e⁻ → Cu⁰ | **+0.34 V** (commonly cited as +0.337 to +0.340 V) | 25 °C, unit activity (a(Cu²⁺) = 1), 1 bar |\n\n> ⚠️ **Note:** This value is **not from NIST SRD-46**. SRD-46 is a stability constants database — it stores equilibrium constants (log β, log K) for metal–ligand complexation reactions in solution, not electrode potentials. For authoritative electrode potential data, consult sources such as the **IUPAC Tables of Standard Electrode Potentials** or the **CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics**.",
